reviewText: I expected less and got so much more. Haylie Duff is amazing! Angie Everhart wow! What a great mix of humor and drama. I laughed at points and teared up at others. And Buddy her dog almost stole the show. Recommended it to my mom and she now wants a DVD. All I can say is The Wedding Pact is a great little movie that men will have no trouble watching with their wives or girlfriends. With all the horror sex and violence in today's films, what a treat to find this little gem. Bravo.

I rented this free on Prime so all I lost was about 1&1/2 hours. It's a boy meets, chases and gets girl movie.

The story is built on the premise that a guy and girl made a 10-year marriage pact in college.

She has forgotten and is marrying a rich jerk because she and mom are going to lose their house.

Enter the rich fiance who buys their house, allowing them an uncomfortable degree of security, as long as the girl marries rich jerk.

Marriage pact guy and girl spend 10 pre-wedding days together before she is due to marry the rich jerk. She falls for marriage pact guy.

In the end, marriage pact guy gets pact-girl but it is not explained how she and/or mother remain stable.

The rich jerk is now out of the picture and pact-guy is not portrayed as terribly wealthy.

In my opinion, the premise that the movie is built on failed.

Hard to watch. It's slow and not very gripping. Tried to watch it twice, both times didn't make it all the way through, though I doubt the ending would have redeemed the movie. I'm a big fan of rom-coms, but this is neither romantic nor funny. Personally I wouldn't feel very flattered that some sleazy guy went on a road trip to marry sad old me after 10 years. Especially not this one. Dunno if they were trying to show the many 'temptations' along the way, but for me it just cemented the guy as a player feeling sorry for himself. Calling every girl Elizabeth for 10 years isn't romantic - that's stupid. If you wanted to be with her you could have done something - see Serendipity ~ A Lot Like Love ~ Forces of Nature ~ While You Were Sleeping... and so on. None of those are my favorite, but at least I enjoyed watching them.

I can't believe I wasted my time watching this to the end, that's just stupidity on my behalf. I don't understand the logic behind this movie. *SPOILER ALERT*  A bunch of 30 year olds are graduating from college, where they're bring out a keg on campus, super realistic. Two best friends from college make a half hearted wedding pact. The guy claims to have fallen in love with her the moment he saw her, which is ridiculous because he knows absolutely nothing about her so he's clearly thinking with his other head. Fast forward 10 years, the guy is having a birthday dinner where the decorations look like it was bought from Party City. His roommate from college shows up and as a present gives him a photo of him and the girl with her address on the back of it. He then decides it's time to find her and collect on their marriage pact. He starts to head to the address on the photo when his friend calls him and tells him she's actually in Hawaii. So he buys a $600 ticket to Hawaii, that ends up going to waste because surprise surprise, she's actually not there! So he gets a call from his friend and she's actually in some other location that I'm not even going to try to recall. So he starts to drive there, stops at a rest stop with no other cars or people there and proceeds to urinate off the mountain. I thought the purpose of a rest stop was so you can urinate indoors. Anyways, a random woman rides to the rest stop on a bike and tries to seduce him. Then she insists he stays the night at her bed and breakfast. How convenient. So he finally arrives at his destination. The college friends haven't spoken for 10 years and yet when he shows up at her house and she still considers him her best friend. Okay fine, that makes perfect sense. And the part I really don't get is how come there are scenes where the two are kissing mouth to mouth like it's perfectly normal for two best friends (one of which, engaged) to kiss like that. They also snuggled together but that I can almost overlook. The mom looks like she's wearing a cheap wig from a children's dress up shop. The only character I liked was the dog.

I think we all remember what our reaction was at the news that Haylie Duff would be starring in a romantic comedy opposite the multifaceted Chris Soldevilla: who the %$#! is Chris Soldevilla? All joking aside, of course we remember him from his stellar performance in the 2000 classic "Coyote Ugly" and eagerly anticipated his performance as Mitch in this film. We were not disappointed. Through forceful performances like this movie, Soldevilla has quietly built a reputation as a major player in the comedy genre, even as he has expanded his range in drama through such vehicles as "7 Minutes" (2014). We all eagerly anticipate future entries in the Soldevilla oeuvre.

But as flawless and nuanced as Soldevilla is in "The Wedding Pact," the real acting tour de force in this film comes from Haylie Duff. We all see in Duff the depth and range of a young Meryl Streep and the wit and witticisms of a youthful Joan Blondell. She doesn't disappoint in this outing. As Elizabeth, Duff has solidified her position as the grand dame of romantic comedies, rivaling the comedic talents of such actresses as Carole Lombard and Edna Purviance.

And who can forget Matt Berman, the wunderkind writer/producer who made this all possible. We all know him from the 2000 masterpiece "F.A.R.T.: The Movie," which the AMPAS shocking passed over in its nominations for a Best Director Oscar. Sam Mendes got lucky with "American Beauty" that year and we all know it. Travesties aside, the Academy will simply not be able to look the other way at Berman's brilliance in "The Wedding Pact" and maintain itself as a legitimate organization.

One cannot find a more scrumptrulescent outing than "The Wedding Pact." Watch and be amazed; talent like this doesn't come along often.

Why did Elizabeth walk all the way to the aisle of her wedding if she had Texas guy waiting with a car to haul her off?  Why did she even need him?  The fiance was never physically abusive, so the "never come looking for her" speech was out of nowhere.  How did the mom know that the fiance hit the dog?  When Elizabeth overheard that, no reaction at all?  If Mitch drove from Boston to California, why did he go through AL, TX, etc.  What kind of mom pushes her daughter to marry such a jerk just to stay in a house? I was fooled by the 3-star rating on Netflix into watching this tripe. It's neither funny nor cute. I really thought it might have been financed by Hilary Duff as a vehicle for her sister, using their friends and family in the cast, that's how bad the acting and the plot is. In the first scene we encounter a group of 30-something looking "college students" celebrating graduation. Guy and girl who are friends offhandedly make a wedding "pact" agreeing that if they have no better prospects in 10 years, they will marry each other. Pretty romantic, right? Wrong! Fast forward ten years and the male lead (who looks like an insurance salesman) is at his birthday party 10 years later when his friend from college shows up. This guy is afraid to fly so his friend tells him he should drive across the country to California to see his sweetheart, but only to Texas, where he is waylaid by a middle-aged redhead at a rest stop--a rest stop without bathrooms, obviously, because he gets out of the car to urinate at the edge of the parking lot. This redhead, who has pedaled up on a bicycle, TO A REST STOP, invites him to her place. I have no idea--why. Somewhere along the line the plans change and the girl is now in Hawaii so he buys a plane ticket and then cancels after realizing he has shared a bottle of booze with the pilot in the waiting area. Terrible, just terrible. I hated everybody in the entire cast by the time 30 minutes was up. I hated everybody who wrote, directed, or paid for this movie to be made. Save yourself a whole lot of angst and skip this movie!!

I don't want to be one of those reviewers that comes out of the dark to just bash a film. I get the whole film process. Someone has a vision, a pretty decent idea, it gets green lit, the cast and crew come together, investors pitch in to get the thing up and running, etc, etc. I hate to slam movies for being terrible when I know a lot of hard work goes into something, and people were just trying to bring their vision to life; whether it be for riches or just the sake of the art. This wasn't for the sake of the art.

The film has a cute premise about a guy and a girl making a pact that if they're not married in ten years, that they'll marry one another. Cute, right? Seems like a family film for all to sit around with popcorn to watch and share a few laughs. WRONG! This film didn't know what it wanted to be. That was my MAIN, MAIN ISSUE! First of all; The film promotes its two female stars: Angie Everhart (90's Swimsuit model, beautiful red head, erotic thriller actress) and Haylie Duff; who is more so known for her famous, Disney sister, Hilary. Oh, and she was semi-relevant ten years ago with Napoleon Dynamite. Has anyone heard of what Jon Heder is up to these days? Anyway, the film markets this as a family comedy, but it's WAY FAR from that. It's like a bunch of frat boys got together and projected out their own fantasies, and wanted this to be a guys movie with a cute female lead, but to mask it as a female comedy that guys may like, yet trick people thinking it's family friendly, only to have it massacred with poor sexual overtones and innuendos...and BAD WRITING! I'm in a tailspin from writing that. That's how jumbled it is.

I love a good R rated comedy. I wish the studios had the balls to make them like they did in the past few decades (70's, 80's, 90's). However, whoever wrote this, doesn't understand women. I am no extreme, radical feminist, but the women that were portrayed in this were God-awful. Throughout the film, I kept thinking it was going to turn into porno at any moment. (Hey, writer and director, there's a good calling), so I was confused. The female characters came off as only serving one purpose; being sexual beings, damsels in distress that can't think for themselves, or a motherly figure. For example: Angie's character thrusting herself on the male lead not even twenty minutes in for no real reason, a random, I'm assuming hooker, thrusting herself on the male lead and then having sex in the car, and a woman feeding a man grapes in lingerie while making a BJ innuendo at the end. This seemed to be a man's fantasy . I got chills down my spine just in embarrassment for all that were involved in this project. You'll know what scenes I'm talking about. Just watch the first fifteen minutes.

I think the leads in this film were decent, overall. The lead male in this film was likable and dynamic. He's a good sidekick, comedy actor. It's a shame he was wasted with this material, as he grated on my nerves after his excessive whining only twenty minutes in. Haylie was a good eye candy and gave a very subtle performance. She's not a bad actress. But note to director and camera people; NEVER shoot/film a woman from the chin up, especially when the camera adds 10-20 pounds. I thought the actor that portrayed her smug fiancé to be very convincing. I've seen his other work and he somehow came out a bit unscathed from the writing. Maybe whoever wrote his smug and cheap character understood him more, therefore, the actor had more wiggle room with the writer. Angie Everhart was cute, but type-cast as a sexual fantasy and lost her Arkansas accent halfway through the movie. She was there for the pay check. Don't blame her. Actors need work, too! Leslie Easterbrook, who played the mom, is from THE DEVILS REJECTS! She was solid, but was destroyed with a bad wig. I hope this film paid her rent and I'll always support her! The script was weak, the directing was flimsy, the cast for the most part did not come out of this unscathed, the editing was choppy, the storyline was too rushed and not cohesive. The soundtrack was decent though, as I was expecting 70's porno music to pop up at any moment. The film didn't have an identity, and I don't know what crowd or target audience it was intended for. I also thought maybe more than one person went into writing this script and directing this, therefore, leaving too many cooks in the kitchen which cause a train wreck like this, or it was one person projecting out their own fantasies in a sloppy manner. I was right. Written and directed by the same person. I rest my case. Maybe this will get reviewed by MST3k. I'd actually only purchase this film to hear the commentary. Now that's where one would pop some pop corn, grab their favorite bottle of liquor, and get their laughs. But I would sue for my seventeen dollars and sanity.

Save your time, money, sanity and whatever else. 1-3/10... and that's being generous. Better luck next time.
